text: I run no walkers.

Lands:

My opinion unless you're in colors abusing having lands in the yard (Gitrog, Splendid Rec) it's not worth having an ETB land on the off-chance you don't need it and can pitch it. The Amonkhet duals are probably worth in that you can fetch them and they're duals, but I am NOT a fan of the mono cyclers unless they're doing double duty regularly. 

Similarly I'd just not run Evolving Wilds or Terramorphic Expanse. The thinning is mathematically irrelevent, and you don't seem to be running stuff that needs a shuffle so they're just mediocre fixing in a deck that doesn't really need it and slows your tempo in the proccess. At the very least I'd run Ash Barrens if you really wanted the effect as it effectively does the same thing and has the option to not be tapped late game when you don't need the fixing. Concealed Courtyard is strictly better, too.

Probably a meta call but IMO decks need at least one if not two land destruction lands now a days.

Cabal Coffers is runnable here but I'm guessing it's not in for budgetary reasons. 

Keep an eye on it as you play but you can probably support Nykthos here. Maybe not, there's a lot of tokens and artifacts, but I bet more often than not it would be mana ahead.


Creatures:

I like Custodi Soulcaller in here, nice call

I've personally soured a bit on Sheoldred. It is an instant bullseye and can wind up dying upon cast, doing nothing. Sepulchral Primordial has been better in my deck (though that's coming out for Elenda) becuase it just always gets something done upon resolution, and if you have ways to recur it like Gift or Volrath's Stronghold it can break the game open. That may just be personal preference though.

Spells:

IMO you need more draw. The only draw ahead sources are Clamp, Arena, and Minion's Murmurs. Recursion is good and kind of compensates, but not enough. I think you'll run out of gas as it stands now. I look at my Teysa deck which probably will play very similarly to this and I have Claim, Arena, Murmurs, Necropotence, Night's Whisper, Read the Bones, Sign in Blood, Decree of Pain, Ambition's Cost, and Ancient Craving, and I'm not entirely sure that's enough. Draw is multiplicative. If you don't have many options you're less likely to draw them in the first place, but the more you have the more likely you are to draw them enabling you to draw more draw. 

I bet if I looked at 10 random decks on EDHREC, 9 would have too little draw by at least half.
I need to upload my list for consideration.
My land base needs work - itâ€™s a â€˜throw togetherâ€™ vs any real tweaks.

I've never ever finished a game and thought "man, things would have gone better if I hadn't drawn so many cards."
